    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Polystichum rhizophorum improperly include experience of vomiting and nausea, due to the presence of thujone, a known neurotoxin found in some ferns. Developing skin irritation is also possible, as some individuals may be allergic to the plant's oils or other compounds. Furthermore, prolonged or excessive consumption of Polystichum rhizophorum may lead to liver damage, as the plant's hepatotoxic properties can cause liver cells to die. Nauseate users is another possible side effect, as the plant's toxic compounds can cause stomach upset and discomfort. These side effects occur because the improper use of Polystichum rhizophorum can lead to an overdose of its toxic compounds, causing harm to the user's health.",
    "uses": "Polystichum rhizophorum has been used in traditional medicine for its potential anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties. In some cultures, it is believed to possess antioxidant and antiviral properties. However, more research is needed to fully understand its medicinal uses. The plant's extracts are thought to have wound-healing and immunomodulatory effects. Further studies are necessary to confirm the efficacy and safety of using Polystichum rhizophorum for medicinal purposes.",
    "taxonomy": "Polystichum rhizophorum is classified within the family Dryopteridaceae. This classification places it within the order Polypodiales, a group of ferns. Further, it is a member of the genus Polystichum, which contains species of shield ferns. Within this genus, Polystichum rhizophorum is a unique species due to its distinctive characteristics. The classification of Polystichum rhizophorum as a species is also supported by its morphological and molecular features.",
    "benefits": "Polystichum rhizophorum, also known as the creeping shield fern, has been traditionally used in folk medicine to treat various health issues. Its health benefits are attributed to the presence of flavonoids, saponins, and other bioactive compounds. The plant has been used to treat respiratory problems, fever, and digestive issues. Additionally, it is believed to have anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties, which may contribute to its potential health benefits. Further research is needed to fully understand the health benefits of Polystichum rhizophorum.",
    "parts": "Polystichum rhizophorum, a type of fern, is used in traditional medicine in various parts of the world. The medicinal parts of this plant include its leaves, roots, and rhizomes. The leaves are rich in antioxidants and are used to treat various health issues, including fever and digestive problems. The roots of Polystichum rhizophorum are believed to have anti-inflammatory properties and are used to treat joint pain and other inflammatory conditions. In traditional medicine, the rhizomes of the plant are used to treat respiratory issues, such as bronchitis and asthma.",
    "intro": "Polystichum rhizophorum, also known as the rhizome-bearing lady fern, is a species of fern that is native to East Asia and is widely distributed across various regions. The health benefits of Polystichum rhizophorum include its ability to reduce inflammation, improve cardiovascular health, and possess antioxidant properties, making it a potential treatment for various diseases. The bioactive constituents of this plant include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and terpenoids, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. Traditionally, Polystichum rhizophorum is used in herbal medicine to make teas, infusions, and tinctures, which are used to treat a range of health issues, including digestive problems and respiratory infections."
